+HARD-PROBLEM STRATEGY (D/E tasks):
+==================================
+- Before coding, restate the constraints (N, Q, value ranges) and estimate the
+  worst-case operation count. If a brute-force approach exceeds ~10^7 basic
+  operations, do NOT submit it; design an O(N log N) or O(N) algorithm first.
+- For counting/combinatorics tasks, consider prefix sums, sorted two-pointer
+  scans, binary search (bisect), and modular arithmetic with precomputed
+  factorials instead of nested loops.
+- For grid/simulation tasks, look for periodicity or state compression before
+  simulating huge step counts.
+- For DP tasks, define the state and transition explicitly in comments before
+  writing code, and verify the DP by hand on the smallest sample.
+- After samples pass, stress-check performance: generate a maximum-size random
+  input and confirm the solution finishes within roughly 2 seconds. If it does
+  not, optimize (e.g., replace Python loops with precomputation, sorting, or
+  math) before finalizing.
+- Use sys.stdin for input parsing on large inputs; avoid per-line input() in
+  hot loops.
+
